Itâ€™s international womenâ€™s day and in Russian culture, this is a HUGE holiday! This is something Iâ€™ve been celebrating since I was a kid and was really surprised that itâ€™s only been recently implemented worldwide like this! In Russia, women get the day off and we receive flowers from family, friends, and loved ones. Itâ€™s a day we celebrate each other! Growing up, I remember waking up and enjoying some sort of cake or Russian pancakes with the table covered in beautiful bouquets of flowers. 

Itâ€™s a beautiful day and Iâ€™m glad itâ€™s become as big as it has been!

Iâ€™ve always been taught to be a tough female. I look to my mom A LOT and the older I become, the more Iâ€™m like her. I stand up for myself, I donâ€™t take shit from ANYONE, I respect myself, and most importantly, Iâ€™m independent.

I donâ€™t rely on anyone. Iâ€™ve worked for everything I have. My parents are hard workers but since Iâ€™ve been young, theyâ€™ve always taught me to go and get the shit I want. And thatâ€™s exactly what Iâ€™m doing. I get down on myself a ton, but Iâ€™m EXACTLY where I want to be.

Iâ€™m glad to say that Iâ€™m confident, independent, and know how to stand up for myself. These are all SUCH important traits for us women to have! Listen to some Cardi B and freaking KNOW YOUR WORTH.

Respect yourself. Respect your body. Respect OTHERS.

Letâ€™s bring each other up. Letâ€™s stop putting other women down. I mean come on! Itâ€™s 2021. We are suchhhh badasses and we need to empower each other. Celebrate success and letâ€™s work on encouraging ourselves to be the best versions of ourselves!

â€” a simple and easy guided meditation. find a comfortable seat and close down the eyes. be fully here with each breath.âœ”ï¸ğŸ§˜â€â™€ï¸

âœ˜ Allow your breath to become soft and natural.

âœ˜ Follow the breath all the way in,
and follow the breath all the way out.

âœ˜ As you breathe, feel the rootedness of your body.

âœ˜ And as we sit, we breathe and connect with the body. All weâ€™re really doing is coming back home, within.

âœ˜ With the breath, we come back home...
again, again, & again...

âœ˜ Inhale the calming, grounding breath.

âœ˜ Exhale and enjoy the feeling of simply arriving.

Take notice on how you feel during the practice. What does it really mean to find a home within? To find stillness? To me, finding home means creating a landing space when I need one. It means having the space to welcome everything and offer full acceptance; to tune in and connect with whatever it is, as it is.ğŸ˜ŒğŸ™Œ

This is me kicking the past self, thoughts, demons, worries & concerns to the curb - 
â€‹
Some of the most vulnerable states & lessons are sincerely taking time to realize you can free yourself from the pain of the past and there are great ways to face your demons.
â€‹
â€‹With the illumination inside of me and forgiveness inside of me, I have been able to face the craziest - painful and hurtful side of me - with grace & love - It hasn't been and wasn't easy, but once it was actually nailed down to see once and for all - the main objective has been to allow nothing but light to shine through awareness and understanding - I have become more aware of my unconscious actions and will never be a victim to them ever again.
â€‹
â€‹We all will or have faced circumstances such as these - but we don't want to talk about it because it might trigger something inside of you - it might bring you back to that scary, worried or fearful place, yet please believe me when I say, you will not know when they will reveal themselves, yet you will know how to respond and react because you know exactly what you are facing now!
â€‹
â€‹You were destined to live an abundant life - just as I am - just as your neighbor is - In order to move on, to be in forward motion, in conjunction to face the negative/demons in your life - which really is just a term for dealing with the repressed or unconscious aspects of your personality - we need to know that everything you desire lies on the other side of facing your demons!
â€‹
â€‹After deep connection with Brendon Burchard's "The Motivation Manifesto" I'm stunned in my walk of facing my demons to be reminded that our internal demons poison us with worry and fear whenever we might be vulnerable, stunting our growth and vitality. Our destiny is decided by how well we know our demons of doubt and delay. How well we defend against them and how many battles we win against them each day of our lives.
â€‹
â€‹â€‹Through Christ giving me my strength, I happily recognize these parts of my life and don't allow the past to be drawn into the future unless we make peace with it.
â€‹

B R E A T H  W O R K O U T

Feeling the need to breathe deeply lately?
-
Try this breath workout.  Expand the belly during inhalation and relax the belly during exhalation.  Let your shoulders drop and jaw relax as you exhale.
-
When you feel angry or anxious breathing can become shallow.  This results in oxygen intake diminishing and muscle tension increasing.  Prolonge your exhalation as this promotes the relaxation response.  This expels the stress and tension from your system and brings you back into the present. 
-
Try this workout:
*Mentally count to 5 for the inhale
*count to 2 as you hold your breath
*count to 8 for the exhale
(15 seconds total for each breath x 4 rounds for a 1 minute breath workout)
-
Practice this when you feel tense or down.  This will help to slow your heart rate, calm your thoughts and find inner stillness in the moment.
-

EMOTIONAL EATING

I have struggled with emotional eating for YEARS. It makes sense, right? Youâ€™re upset, feeling down, out of control, why not turn towards food? Food gives you control, it triggers your endorphins, it satisfies. 

I would constantly turn to sweets when I had a rough day at work, if I was tired to perk me up, and when I just wanted comfort. It got to the point where Iâ€™d hide food wrappers from my parents or boyfriend because I felt so ashamed. Iâ€™d lie and say that I was starving,  when I just ate, so I could eat a second meal out with friends. I felt so fearful of judgement.

But at the end of the day, what I thought had given me control, really left me out of control all together. 

Now that I practice macro tracking, or flexible dieting, I can allow myself little treats when I want while still reaching my personal goals. I can truly have chocolate everyday, or a bagel and oatmeal in the same day. And with that freedom, that is the ULTIMATE CONTROL I was looking for all along. 

If you struggle with this too, know youâ€™re not alone and Iâ€™m always here if you need support â¤ï¸

Hereâ€™s how you figure it out and how to stop stressing over the perfect number, because there is no such thing.

First you should learn your body and fully understand your hunger cues.

Does that mean you track your food or you eat intuitively?

Either, pick the one thatâ€™s right for you.

Tracking is a great tool and it will definitely help you achieve your goals.

Intuitive eating meaning- your diet consists of Whole Foods and the other delicious foods out there but in a way thatâ€™s not going to make you feel horrible. Like tracking but not tracking.

When you allow your body to enjoy the foods that itâ€™s eating, living more of a carefree lifestyle and providing it with the proper nutrients, you will find that your weight is going to land where it should.

I believe that we are all built differently and that we all are meant to have a weight range.

We love fiber, but unfortunately, most people donâ€™t eat enough of it.

The RDA (recommended daily amount), according to the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics is 25 grams for women and 38 grams for men OR 14 grams per 1,000 calories consumed.

The majority of new clients come to me eating less than that on a consistent basis. How much is right for you will vary, however, 25 grams (for women) is a good number to aim for. If youâ€™re super low on fiber to start, make sure you SLOWLY increase your intake over time. You also need to make sure youâ€™re staying consistent with your intake on a daily basis (30 grams one day and 4 grams the next isnâ€™t going to cut it).

Fiber is not only important for digestion, but it also increases satiety (keeps you full for longer) and helps regulate blood sugar and blood cholesterol (among many other things). My top 6 (because I couldnâ€™t pick just 5) favorite sources of fiber include old fashioned oats, ground flaxseed, raspberries, avocado, chickpea pasta, and salad bowls packed with veggies and allll the micros like this one from @dailycleanfoodanddrink pictured here ğŸ˜‹

And just like that its been a year (and a few days ğŸ˜‚) since I started running with my coach, @billbrumbachocr . The timing of it all was somewhat serendipitous - I had been wanting to work on my running for quite some time and I finally got my shit together and started in March 2020 - right before the world shut down. Previously I always had trouble running more than 2-3 miles because my knees would always hurt. I never paid attention to my heart rate. And I always had such a hard time recovering from long runs. The world was still fairly normal the first week I did Bill's programming and I would head down to Sports and Wellness to use their treadmills to get my runs done. Fast forward two weeks, the world basically shut down and I had to move my runs outside. Man oh man. What a year it has been. All of these benchmarks I have accomplished within this past year - with my most recent PR - my 1 mile from last Tuesday. I never thought I could run that fast much less run in the cold. It's one thing running on a treadmill, it's a whole other beast getting out and propelling yourself to run FAST on the road and the trials. Throughout the year I have seen and been through so much on my runs. I've explored around the city and have so much more to explore! I have found something that is super sustainable for my body - I can run 3 hours one day and have recovered enough to run 90 minutes the next day. My knees don't hurt after 2-3 miles. I am so incredibly thankful that I have the coach that I do. Bill - you are awesome. You are an amazing coach and an amazing friend and I can't wait to see what I can accomplish with your guidance over this next year!

Why waste time proving over and over how great you are, when you could be getting better? Why hide deficiencies instead of overcoming them? Why look for friends or partners who will just shore up your self-esteem instead of ones who will also challenge you to grow? And why seek out the usual, instead of experiences that will stretch you?

Dig a little deeper and you may discover that your mindset isn't as dynamic as you previously thought. People with a growth mindset constantly challenge their self-limiting beliefs and personal bests. They take criticism without taking it personally. Crucially, they know when they're in their comfort zone, just as they know that personal growth isn't always comfortable.

For todayâ€™s workout, I did some cardio on my spin bike then finished my workout off with some glute exercises. One of the moves I did was bridges. This move always works your hamstrings as well. If you want to add more resistance, you can add on weights while doing them.

2. Lift off the ground and hold for 2 seconds and bring it back down. 
3. When you bring your hips up, make sure you squeeze your glutes. 

Beginners: 15 reps, rest 15 seconds, repeat 3 to 5 times. 
Advanced: 30 reps, rest 5 seconds, repeat 5 to 8 times.

caption:
Back with another dirty workout in the pain cave gym!!!

â˜˜ï¸I love drop sets because they allow you to burn out a muscle group and get a ton of reps in a short amount of time. 

â˜˜ï¸A drop set is what it sounds like- you literally drop weight off and immediately go into the next set up reps. For example, I started with 8 heavy hip thrusts, dropped a plate and went immediately into 10 reps, dropped the weight, and finished with 12 body weight reps. All of these sets will finish with body weight reps!

â˜˜ï¸ The last round is a combo move where you donâ€™t put the bar down until you finish all the exercises- so go directly into each exercise after you finish 5 reps! The exercises should flow into one another

â˜˜ï¸ I added 5 minutes of steady biking before each new circuit to keep my heart rate high but you can always do some jump roping, jumping jacks, etc to keep your heart rate high!

â˜˜ï¸ screenshot the end or bookmark this workout to save! It took me about an hour!!!

Over the next few days I will be sharing 5 different movements for de-stressing your body. Particularly for those of you who have been working long hours at home during the pandemic. 
-
Today is day 2 - The Cat/Cow
-
-
This video offers a quick tutorial on how to keep mobility throughout your body by flexing and extending the spine. 
-
Most of us, who work from home, spend countless hours haunching over a computer screen. This can cause unnecessary strain, and even damage, to our bodies. 
-
Take breaks through the work day to: walk, move, stretch, squat, lunge, rotate, reach, flex, and what-the-f-ever-else; JUST GET UP and MOVE! 
-
A great trick is to set a timer for every 2 hours; try to complete 3-5 stretches before you go back to work. Also, It is a good habit to stand as much as possible while working at a computer; there are tons of standing desk options available. 

-
Lastly, be mindful with core stacking, breathing, bracing, and tension. Check all the boxes and youâ€™ll notice you wonâ€™t feel as stiff and achy anymore.

Insights into athleticism and #MakeLittAthleticAgain: multiplanar power.

If you've been watching, you've seen me add a load of lateral movements into my training in the last few weeks. Most of them have been strength based, working to increase the ability to produce forces in the frontal and transverse planes. 

With the goal of being more athletic approaching more rapidly then I thought, I've begun to add more multiplanar power work. Power is a byproduct of force and velocity, so the goal is to produce force quickly, and do so in multiple planes of motion.

I incorporated this Medball slam into my training the other day as part of fitting within that goal: moving through both the frontal and transverse planes (think lateral and rotational), and moving at lighter loads that can be moved quickly. The reactive/rebounding component was added for my pure enjoyment.

I almost always say three time's a charm when we practice deep asanas. ğŸ’«

The first time is getting a feel for what we're about to do, the entrance, the engagement, the exit. The second time, less assisted, I want to make sure they're capable, focused and in control. The third time, I'm on standby. They do what they can and I'm ready in arms reach.

This is one of those poses where the third time almost felt like I was dying and I wouldn't ask for it three times, especially on the bad side haha! Entering and exiting with composure makes it even more challenging. Anyone else feel this way with this dancer variant? ğŸ˜†ğŸ™ˆ

Deep crimson and tan rocks, rolling grasslands, and sandy washes await you at Red Mountain Open Space, a 15,780-acre open space in northeastern Colorado.
.
From the trailhead, hikers, bikers, and horseback riders can take off on over 15 miles of multi-use trails.
.
Some of the first humans in North America resided here over 12,000 years ago, and people have lived and worked this land since. Out of respect for these cultures, collection of any artifact is strictly prohibited. It is up to each of us to help preserve the ecological and cultural integrity of this area.
.

My only goal for this class was to try to breathe. Itâ€™s funny breathing has come up a number of times in recent weeks from the people that I trust as something I need to work on. Breathing...that thing our bodies do autonomously to live.
ğŸ¤
Iâ€™m usually in a revved up state, searching for the next challenge, geared up for the next workout or seeking a thrill. What Iâ€™m not good at is slowing down and just breathing, giving my nervous system a break. Iâ€™m also restricted around my ribs from tight muscles leaving some potential for oxygen uptake on the table (more oxygen is kinda useful in endurance sports). So @hughespt_yyc gave me some breathing exercises to address both of those. Iâ€™m going to make an effort to take some time and focus on breathing, letting the tension go and just chill a bit more.

Be intentional in creating the physical foundation of the pose and be up to something bigger than yourself.

This is the first organizing principle of True North Alignment. 

Build a strong foundation in each pose by working from the ground up. Put your attention on specific body parts starting with what is touching the mat (think your feet or hands). From that stable foundation you create physical integration and expand out.

When your foundation is solid, nothing can take you down.

â€œWhat is the best training split?â€

Answer - There is no one best training split.

The best training split for YOU is probably going to be different than the best training split for me, your friend, your significant other, etc..

Just because somebody else is seeing results while following a certain training split doesnâ€™t mean you have to follow that same split to see results yourself.

You can have success training 2-3 days per week, 4-5 days per week, OR 6 days per week. You can have success training for 45 minutes at a time OR 1-2 hours at a time. See a pattern here?

The most important thing is that you are following a program YOU can adhere to - one that works for your body, fits your lifestyle, and one you enjoy.

With an efficiently programmed training plan, you CAN be successful with what best fits your schedule and lifestyle. I am proof. My clients are proof. Even @frommy20 is proof ğŸ¤­ğŸ˜‰ There are so many ways to make progress and the best way is going to be doing things that work best for you. Make your training split fit your lifestyle, make it enjoyable, and stay consistent. THAT is what really matters.

Becoming a coach with Beachbody has probably been the best decision I have made.

Growing up I always was into sports and had that community type of feeling. We cheered each other on we had goals to look forward to!

Fast forward to college; I was majoring in nursing, and had that support group. And then I moved to NC. All I did was go to work, eat and sleep. I had nothing to look forward to. I started binging on Netflix and stress eating. I. Was. Miserable.

Fast forward to June of 2018 I saw my now coach on my discovery page and realized I wanted to do whatever she was doing.

She got in shape. Looked happy. Had an amazing community of friends...AND was a nurse. I reached out to her.

The second I reached out I decided I was going to coach because I craved the community.

 I craved the support each woman gave each other! It wasnâ€™t all about me...it was a we effort.

We all clapped for each otherâ€™s success.

I watched teachers, nurses, doctors, lawyers all leave their full time jobs for coaching.

It gives me chills.

If you are looking for a group to empower you to do your absolute best, this is for you!

You are never alone. You are never stuck. We are here for you!

Ladies..Lost your period from working out? Listen up.

What is the female athlete triad?

Three interrelated factors including energy availability, menstrual function and bone mineral density 

When energy availability is low (in the case of a low number of calories taken in and high amount of energy expended) females can develop menstrual irregularities. 

Prolonged periods of low energy availability along with lack of mensuration will then eventually impact bone mineral density of a female athlete 

Protein, calcium and vitamin D all play a pivotal role in keeping BMD high. 

As bones decline in structure and deteriorate there becomes and even bigger risk for fractures.. specifically for athletes stress fractures 

What can you do? 

1. First, consult with your doctor. If they tell you this is normal, be skeptical 
2. Make sure you are consuming adequate calories to suite your personal needs 
3. Consume protein, ideally from lean sources such as poultry, low fat dairy, fish, lean beef, lentils etc

Pay attention to signs 

1. Sleep quality
2. Overall energy/mood 
3. Recovery from training

The theme this year is "Choose to Challenge" which is the absolute perfect theme for me this year. I just finished my 45 day challenge with @f45_training_westparkridge
and couldn't be happier with my results!

I have always worked out on the reg and watched what I ate. Once gyms opened back up after COVID I got right back to it. I was killing myself every day but wasn't seeing any results! I wondered why. Once they told us about the 45 day challenge I knew it was something I needed to participate in. I have never been one for fad diets or anything like that. Eating right is a lifestyle choice and something I have always stuck with. I have never cut out any food groups (which you can read about in one of my blog posts) you need to make sure you're eating from each and every one just in moderation! I know what works best for me and which foods I should stay clear from. You need to learn your body and what works for you. For some reason the way I use to eat was no longer working for me. They say your body changes every 7 years so I guess my time was up! It was time to start recording my food intake and really pay attention to calories and micronutrients which I have never done before.

I am currently down 6.6 lbs (which isn't much for 45 days but it's a good start).
Lost 2 inches in my waist.
Lost 2 1/2 inches in my hips.
Lost 1 inch in my arms.
Lost 1/2 inch in my chest and thighs.

I can see the changes in my body which makes me want to push myself even more.

This picture was taken about half way through the challenge and before I had to take 10 days off due to testing positive for COVID. I felt defeated at that point. I was doing so good and thought I would end up back at square one with not working out for 10 days. Boy was I wrong! #iwd2021

What are you going to challenge yourself with this year?!

1. Lift up through the crown of your head, reach your fingertips forward and hinge your body up and back. Bring one leg up, out, in and down. Same leg 4x. Switch legs. 
2. Hands behind you, fingertips facing toward your butt, slight bend in the arms. Scissor switch the legs with pointed toes and straight knees. 6 sets. 
3. Keep the same arms as the previous exercise, heels together toes apart, flexed feet. Bend the knees in towards you and straighten the legs back out. 6x. 
4. Scissor switches again. 6 sets. 
5. Keep the arms where the are, bend the knees in towards the chest, legs glued together and feet are flexed. Bend knees in, straighten legs out. 6x. 
6. Turn the legs out once again. Same exercise as #3 to finish off!

Would like to start by saying Happy International Womenâ€™s Day to all the badass women-identifying people I know ğŸ¥ºğŸ¤ I am a better woman because of the people I have in my life, including the support of so many of you!

Today weâ€™re going to quickly run down some of the common variations of deadlifts out there as Iâ€™ve gotten many questions for clarification!

1ï¸âƒ£RDLs/Romanian Deadlifts: often done with dumbbells and very similar to a traditional deadlift. The main difference being how far the chest comes over the feet as well as the fact that the weights do not touch the floor, but rather stop at about shin height. The knees are slightly bent, and the glutes/hips hinge backwards
2ï¸âƒ£Stiff-Legged Deadlifts: very similar to the RDL with chest position and weights not touching the floor, but legs stay more straight (a SLIGHT bend is okay, but legs should be mostly straight)
3ï¸âƒ£Barbell Deadlift: weight starts on the floor, and comes back to the floor between each rep (whether it be tap-and-go or resetting each time). You generally sit a little deeper in the starting position, with your legs bent a bit more, and your chest higher and further back

All of these seem quite similar and follow the same movement pattern, but they incorporate different fibres from different muscle groups and should be varied in your programs intentionally! 

As per usual, if you wanted to save this for your next deadlift day or to check up on your form, I would really appreciate your support ğŸ¤ğŸ¤ğŸ¤

Do your neck, back, shoulders feel tight all the time? What about persistent back pain or aching? Tension headaches? How you breathe could be a big component.

We take as many as 15,000 breaths or more per day. You better believe that how we do something fifteen THOUSAND times, day in and day out, will affect how we feel.

If youâ€™re not breathing with your diaphragm, then youâ€™re probably using your shoulder, upper chest, and neck muscles to drive each inhale. These are your â€œaccessory breathing muscles,â€ which are supposed to help you breathe only when youâ€™re respirating as hard as you can, like at the end of a sprint. They are not supposed to be breathing for you all the time. But persistent stress, poor movement variability, and lack of practice/awareness can lead to them taking over.

What happens when you use an accessory system as your primary way to breathe, 15,000 times, every day? It will start to feel tight, no matter how much stretching you do. Imagine squeezing your hand all day - itâ€™s going to feel tight! 

And because it connects to your low back, under activity of the diaphragm will start to affect how the low back feels as well.

Breathing has gotten a lot of hype recently, and while not a miracle cure for everyone, itâ€™s certainly a big piece we canâ€™t ignore.

Good morning team. Happy Monday. We always say new week new opportunities all around us just gotta be willing to look and embrace. 

I wanted to talk a little today about hip abduction. I see regularly in the gym a over use of bands and abductions machines. Now I say this with absolutely no judgement. There was a time when we were told in order to build great Glutes we required bands and loads of abduction work. Iâ€™m here to tell you this couldnâ€™t be further from the truth. Banding squats, hip thrusts and always taking a wide stance is not optimal for Glute growth. In fact research is now showing the Glute max is more efficiently trained in a narrow position. 

In order to build great Glutes we need to ficus predominately on the Glute max. This is the largest muscle. We target with compound movements. Squats, deadlifts, lunges, split squats. 

I talk to a lot of women and a large majority of them suffer from lower back pain, hip issues and Glutes they wish were bigger. Tons of abduction work is most definitely the culprit here. When we pull the work out of the targeted muscle which is much larger and put it into a much smaller one the body will respond and its not usually good. Sacrum, piriformis, hips all take the brunt here team. 

Here is a effective exercise to add at the end of a lower body workout. Light weight! 

A cable abduction 
2 sets 20 per side 
Rest 30 secs

Revolved hand to foot (aka â€œdancing Shivaâ€) - Parivrtta Hasta Padangusthasana 

Shiva is known as the destroyer because he breaks things down for us so that even better things can come into place. The name â€œShivaâ€ can be translated to mean the â€œgoodâ€ or â€œbenevolent one.â€ The destruction can occur in relation to any aspects of ourselves which does not serve us, such as certain parts of our ego or the obstacles that may get in our way of having happiness and contentment in our lives. 

One example of this can be when a relationship or a job ends, and we might see this as a TERRIBLE thing, but we later realize that it was for the best. As a counselor, I often help people through some very difficult break ups. At first, they are devastated, sad, and can see no â€œlightâ€ at the end of the tunnel. In the end, the clients often realize that they are finding even greater happiness following the ending of the relationship. They are finding greater self confidence and less anxiety because they often realize (later) that the relationship was not healthy overall. 

Yoga, as a practice, also helps us to break down old patterns and thoughts which no longer serve us to make room for even better behaviors and thoughts. Case in point, I have continued to find eating habits that are in my best interest. I continuously learn more about my body and which supplements and foods work the best for me.

-
Take breaks through the work day to: walk, move, stretch, squat, lunge, rotate, reach, flex, and what-the-f-ever-else; JUST GET UP and MOVE! 
-
A great trick is to set a timer for every 2 hours; try to complete 3-5 stretches before you go back to work. Also, It is a good habit to stand as much as possible while working at a computer; there are tons of standing desk options available.

Mobility Monday

I love the overhead squat because of the overall demands it places on the body. 

Though it is very impressive to put up big numbers, I generally use the overhead squat more for mobility purposes. I have found that if I can comfortably get into an overhead squat, my entire body is generally feeling great! 

I messed around this morning with some close grip overhead squats to work on mobility. Notice that I didnâ€™t add any weight! Mainly because each progression of narrowing the hands makes the movement more and more difficult.

I have always said that one should able to overhead squat more than they bench press! 

Try a broom stick or empty barbell first. Loading this movement is NOT necessary. Just getting into the position can be tricky!

To the women who raised me, supported me, challenged me. The ones who have stayed with me through my highs and my lows. The ones who remain a constant inspiration and my best humans around. To the women that taught me lessons over time that our paths have moved on. To those who remain no matter what! To the incredible women and paths I have yet to cross ğŸ’œ

So hereâ€™s to strong women. May we know them. May we be them. May we raise them.

A few years ago I made it my mission to change, support and strengthen women physically, mentally and emotionally not only in my personal life but also my career. Itâ€™s been the biggest game changer seeing women turn their lives around for themselves.

We all have our battles.

Rise up together, be kind & support one another. Things Iâ€™ve learnt that are so basic but go a long way. Be the person of change to another womanâ€™s life:

1). Smile - it goes a long way
2). Ask how they are & listen to what they have to stay
3). Pay another woman a compliment, vocalise it â¤ï¸
4). Be your own superhero
5). Donâ€™t be afraid to ask for what you want
6). When someone is hurting there pain will negatively project onto you - rise up. The best response is no response. Those who are with you will support you.
7). Build each other up - confidence over shaming & guilt tripping one another
8). Lead the way for the next generation. Pay attention to how you speak to yourself, handle yourself but how youâ€™re turning up around the younger generation.

Strong is Sexy!!!!!! Hereâ€™s to all of my Queens pushing boundaries, believing in themselves and turning up against all odds!

YOU DO YOU, FOR YOU! & all the Queens who need your magic!

Happy International Day ladies - if youâ€™re struggling and I can help in anyway send me a DM, donâ€™t be shy, be brave and letâ€™s make your day shine â˜€ï¸

â–ªï¸this is not necessarily for everyone and anyone. If you struggle with reoccurring injuries, joint pain, mobility issues...this might not be for you due to the high volume.
â–ªï¸make sure you have the movement pattern down and your form is solid. Yes I have to work on my deadlift still but Iâ€™d say that I move quite safely and am not putting spine or body in general at risk. 
â–ªï¸pick a weight that you can do for 20reps roughly 60% of your 1RM. 
â–ªï¸rest for about 60-90sec if youâ€™re simply repeating one exercise for the 10 sets. 
â–ªï¸ MY TEMPO NEEDS WORK. Itâ€™s funny how when youâ€™re doing the lift you feel like youâ€™re going at a good pace but looking back at the video Iâ€™m like sis, hold the heck up. Control that  dang eccentric!!! 
Anywho this goes back to the whole, â€œhey cutie, YOU DO NOtttt NEED TO OVERCOMPLICATE YOUR TRAINING!!!â€ Learn the basics, practice the basics, master the basics. And dont be afraid to enjoy the moments between the sets. Wheymen.

Cognitive Dissonance: the state of having inconsistent thoughts, beliefs, or attitudes, especially as relating to behavioral decisions and attitude change.

This theory was my FAVORITE in all of my communication courses in college because it plays such a big part in our lives.

Our brain craves consistency. You canâ€™t say & believe one thing and then expect to act the opposite way.

You canâ€™t constantly say â€œIâ€™m not a morning personâ€ and expect to try to create a new habit of waking up early. You canâ€™t say â€œI donâ€™t like the way healthy food tastes,â€ and then expect to change your eating habits. 

If you want to create new, healthier habits, you have to start thinking & showing up as the type of person who already has those habits.

So, start saying â€œI am a morning person,â€ if you want to start waking up earlier. If you want to start eating more nutrient dense foods & have a healthier relationship with food, start saying â€œI eat to fuel my body & donâ€™t believe in â€˜goodâ€™ or â€˜badâ€™ foods.â€

The easiest way to create the best version of yourself is to believe that you already are that person, and start showing up as her every single day. 

Letâ€™s go get better today!

Welcome to week 2 of March Mindfulness! This week is all about getting grounded in ourselves. To be grounded means to be rooted in the present moment, like a tree that stands firm in the middle of natural disaster. A sense of calm & peace while chaos surrounds it.

To be a tree is impossible, youâ€™re human. But to learn from a tree holds value. We all have thoughts that burden us & make us feel like weâ€™re running a million miles a minute, bouncing from one to the next, getting so lost in them that we forget to be present. But being able to stay rooted while the turmoil of your thoughts are swirling around you & not let it take you with it is powerful.

From that place, we can observe our thoughts rather than getting swept up in them. 

Anxious feeling is a natural part of being human & its not going to magically disappear. Itâ€™s challenging to navigate, thats why this week I wanted to focus on giving you a way to find your center & inner calm when theres a storm brewing ğŸ¤

2ï¸âƒ£Phase 2: Fat loss to expose the muscle you just built and appear â€œtonedâ€ by eating in a caloric deficit, possibly adding additional cardio, and continuing a progressive overload based program. â£

caption:
â–FLAT FEET?â–

No you donâ€™t need any fancy shoes you need to strengthen up your feet! Try these 4 moves to strengthen the arch in your foot, and decrease foot pain that comes along with flat feet! 

On top of these 4 moves, make sure that when you train you go shoeless when possible to better strengthen your feet and receive stronger nerve signals from ground contact! Aka better muscle activation âœ”ï¸ 

1) Foot grabs- imagine your feet are hands and gather the ground with your foot creating the arch

2) Standing calf raises- lift up to your tips toes, hold, release to ground slowly 

3) Toes elevated, side rocks- keeping toes off the ground the entire time rock from the ankles side to side slowly, keeping legs/knees straight 

4) Arch trigger point- using a lacrosse ball, tennis ball, KB handle- anything you can find and dig into that arch to help release tension and lengthen. 

Try each move 12-15 reps for 3 rounds as a warmup before every training or cardio session! Remember your feet hold your entire body so hereâ€™s your reminder to show them some love and care âœ¨ğŸ¤âœ”ï¸ #flatfeet

A proper warmup should prepare the body for whatâ€™s to come efficiently to help avoid injury, improve range of motion, increase fat burning, and exercise output! 

Whatâ€™s a proper warmup up look like: 

1) 5-8 min of low to moderate intensity cardio increasing intensity over time. (EX: treadmill walk, start at incline 2% and increase by 1% every minute maintaining same brisk walking speed).

2) 3-5min of Dynamic movements/stretches targeting the same joints to be trained in the workout. 

3) 5-8min Movement prep, again mimicking the movements you will be training, under lower loads at full range of motion. Use this time to also do any necessary muscle activation and postural set up.
